Queens Boulevard, north side, west of Fifty-fifth Ave., to Broadway, showing in 4 views the Old Presbyterian Church and Cemetery of Newtown. The Church was destroyed by fire in May 1929. See other views. The rest of the buildings in this view were all demolished by Mar. 1, 1931. This church was erected in 1787 on site of a former one destroyed by the British during the Revolutionary War. Dr. John P. Knox was pastor from 1855 to 1882. At this time square pews with little doors were installed.

Queens Boulevard, east side, from 55th Avenue (left) to near 56th Avenue, showing the area in two successive views. These homes appear on maps as early as 1873. The first three homes from the left (view 1) were then owned by H. Geisling; the little house to the right of these, by one G.B.; and the house with the dormer windows, as well as the one adjoining it on the right, by Mrs. Raymond. To the right of that, standing in the direct path of the proposed extension of 55th Road, is the J. Casey house. The two small houses in the center of view 1 are on the direct line of 55th Avenue, when the latter will be extended here; the houses on the left will then occupy the N.E. corner of the intersection.

P. L. Sperr

July 2, 1935
Views 1,2
